{
  "texts": [
    "Early warning of nutrient application issues can save operators significant time and labor expenses.",
    "First, our results using the VI-AE demonstrate that selecting the appropriate VI is crucial to the model's success, and that even the top features evolve in their detection efficacy over the course of the experiment (Figure 2).",
    "Different VIs may be better suited for monitoring anomalies at different growth stages, with NDWI median showing most promise for early growth periods (with 71% average net detection of T3 until window length 12) and GNDVI median for later growth (73% average net detection of T3 for the longest five windows).",
    "Although net detection rates of T2 were lower than T3, with a 65% net detection using GNDVI for a 7-day window and a 67% net detection using GRVI with a 9-day window, significant losses could be averted using this early warning protocol prior to deeper analysis.",
    "Early plant growth can be especially sensitive to nutrient and water stress, when small leaves are thin and will allow shorter wavelengths to be reflected by biochemical constituents, making indicators like NDWI promising for the detection of differences."
  ]
}